Highlight Data Ranges with Conditional Formatting

You can highlight field values reports based on ranges and colors you specify. This feature is available in summary and matrix reports.

To enable conditional highlighting, your report must contain at least one summary field or custom summary formula.

In Lightning Experience, you can set up to five rules and define custom colors for each range. Click Conditional Formatting and select a summary or custom summary formula field that serves as a KPI for your business. Set the breakpoint values and their range colors for each bin.

In Salesforce Classic, click Show | Conditional Highlighting in report builder, then set the breakpoint values and their range colors as follows:

* Summary: Choose a summary field whose number ranges you want represented by colors.
* Low Color: Select a color to represent data that falls below the Low Breakpoint value.
* Low Breakpoint: The number that acts as the threshold between the Low Color and the Mid Color.
* Mid Color: Select a color to represent data that falls between the Low Breakpoint and High Breakpoint values.
* High Breakpoint: The number that acts as the threshold between the Mid Color and the High Color.
* High Color: Select a color to represent data that falls above the High Breakpoint value.

When you apply more than three conditional formatting rules, conditional formatting can be viewed and edited only in Lightning Experience.
title: Highlighting Data Ranges with Conditional Formatting
